{{Refimprove|date=December 2021}}
'''To''' (斗) is a unit of {{ill|Volume|en|Volume|WD=Q39297|lt=volume|1=Volume}} in the {{ill|Japanese units of measurement|en|Japanese units of measurement|WD=Q1029751|lt=Shakkanhō|1=Japanese units of measurement}} system.

{{Unit
|Name=To (斗)
|System={{ill|Japanese units of measurement|en|Japanese units of measurement|WD=Q1029751|lt=Shakkanhō|1=Japanese units of measurement}} (multiple unit)
|Quantity={{ill|Volume|en|Volume|WD=Q39297|lt=Volume|1=Volume}}
|Definition=10 {{ill|Sheng (volume)|en|Sheng (volume)|WD=Q995076|lt=Shō|1=Sheng (volume)}}
|SI=Approx. 18.039 L (Japan)<br/>10 L (China)
|image=
|Caption=An 18-liter can
}}

1 {{ill|Sheng (volume)|en|Sheng (volume)|WD=Q995076|lt=Shō|1=Sheng (volume)}} equals 1/10 of a To, and 10 To equals 1 {{ill|Koku|en|Koku|WD=Q855048|lt=Koku (unit)|1=Koku}}. In Japan, during the {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|WD=Q3125096|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era}}, 1 shō was standardized to approximately 1.8039 liters, making 1 to approximately 18.039 liters.

In China, 1 shō was defined as 1 liter, making 1 to equivalent to 10 liters. Although no longer in practical use in modern China, "斗" was used historically to represent 10 liters (1 decaliter, daL) in the {{ill|Metric system|en|Metric system|WD=Q232405|lt=Metric system|1=Metric system}}, sometimes referred to as "公斗" in Chinese. The {{ill|Market System (Chinese)|ja|市制|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Market System (Chinese)|1=Q11059428|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11059428}} unit "市斗" also corresponds to 10 liters. However, the value of the to varied over different historical periods, generally increasing over time. For example:
- During the {{ill|Zhou dynasty|en|Zhou dynasty|WD=Q35216|lt=Zhou dynasty|1=Zhou dynasty}}, 1 to was 1.94 liters.
- During the {{ill|Qin (state)|en|Qin (state)|WD=Q34756|lt=Qin dynasty|1=Qin (state)}}, it was 3.43 liters.
- In the {{ill|Han_dynasty#Eastern_Han|en|Han_dynasty#Eastern_Han|WD=Q7209|lt=Later Han|1=Han dynasty}}{{citation needed|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Later Han|qq=}}, it was reduced to 1.98 liters.
- It increased to 2.02 liters during the {{ill|Cao Wei|en|Cao Wei|WD=Q320930|lt=Wei|1=Cao Wei}} and {{ill|Western Jin|ja|西晋|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Western Jin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Western Jin Dynasty|WD=Q1145470}} dynasties.
- During the {{ill|Sui dynasty|en|Sui dynasty|WD=Q7405|lt=Sui dynasty|1=Sui dynasty}} and {{ill|Tang dynasty|en|Tang dynasty|WD=Q9683|lt=Tang dynasty|1=Tang dynasty}}, it reached 5.94 liters.
- By the {{ill|Ming dynasty|en|Ming dynasty|WD=Q9903|lt=Ming dynasty|1=Ming dynasty}}, it grew to 10.74 liters, close to its modern value.

In Japan, a rectangular {{ill|Tinplate|en|Tinplate|WD=Q2556927|lt=tin|1=Tinplate}} can with a volume of about 1 to was historically called an {{ill|Itto-kan|ja|一斗缶|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itto-kan|1=itto-kan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11352719}} ("1-to can"). After {{ill|World War II|en|World War II|WD=Q362|lt=World War II|1=World War II}}, the name "5-gallon can" (5 USG = 18.93 liters) became widespread, but it was later officially renamed the "18-liter can." {{ill|Plastic|ja|プラスチック|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Plastic|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 合成樹脂|1=Synthetic resin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1418040}} containers (commonly known as {{ill|Poly tank|ja|ポリタンク|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Poly tank|1=polyethylene tank|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11339307}}) for holding substances such as kerosene were developed as replacements for itto-kan. These containers typically have a capacity of 1 to (18 liters) or slightly more, such as 20 liters.

